{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_protoss_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656240/1908032501/0050.xml":{"full_text":"nSiTCORRUPI\nReport on Charges Against\nJudge Wilfley.\nWILL NOT BE IMPEACHED\nMay Have Been Harsh and HighHanded\nin His Ways.\nBETRAYED LEGAL IGNORANCE\nHeld American in Shanghai on a\nWrong Charge. But Without\nMalicious Intent.\nImpeachment proceedings will not bi:\ninstituted in the 1'nited States Senate\nagainst Lebbous R. Wilflcy. judge of the\nVnited Stales court for t'hina, as a result\nof the charges misbehavior i:i office\nbrought against him hy J.oriti Andrews\nand other American lawyers resident in\nShanghai. The report of the special\nlonnnitt'-e. consisting of Represents!lives\nAl'ion of IVnnsylvania. Wehh of North\n?\"aro!ina sind Diekema of Michigan, appointed\nhy Speaker <'anvtou* to determine\nw: ether the charges were based upon\nfai is sufficient to warrant impeachment\nof Judge Wiltlev. today submitted its rep-el\nto t lie House committee on the judiciary.\nThis report is in tne nature of\nverdht. holding Jr.dge Wilffey guiltless\n?>l the bad motives necessary to a legal\ncause for impeachment, but finding him\nguilty?though more hy forceful implication\nthan by direct accusation?of highhandedness\nand harshness, and some serious\nmistakes in the conduct of his court.\nThe investigation by the special eonimutec\nfollowed the itit reduction in Hie\nHouse by Mr. Waldo of New York of a\nn.-unorial comprising twenty-nine distiiiey\n1 urges made by Mr. Andrews and ids\ni nll( hl-iics lu tin- i-? riori of the commit\ntee an exhaustive review, written by Chairman\nMnun atu'i concurred in by Mr. Webb\n.itiil Mr. Uiekema. each of tliese charges\nand i he real facts relating thereto, as\nin ought out by the testimony taken, are\nudieially discussed and disposed of. and\nthe conclusions reacited are as follows;\nImpeachment Not Warranted.\nT conclusion of the committee deduced\nfrom tiie memorial, from the examination\nof petitioner and from our ton.-t'ta-tion\nof the precedenis of Impeach-;\nleft trials in the I'nited Slates :s. that\na tuai facts charged in the said me-\ntnorial. even though established by com-;\npfteni l\"gal evidence. would not justify a\nonvb-ti.oi of Judge Wilflpy upon charges'\ni>' impeachment before the I'nited States\nSenate, and would not. therefore, warrant\na presentation by the House of Kepr?-s.-iita:i\\es\nof su -li articles of impeachment.\"\nAtno.g the charges brought against\nttfiu :it 11*? 1 *i?s\n.Minrity i'l prescribing examinations to\nl i.ik' ii t?\\ attorneys rtpsiring to prarin\nhis court. notwithstanding they\nliad iif.-n admitted to tlie highest federal\ni. nts o- the Tinted States and were possej-sen\nof ia:r reputation. The committee\nfinds that i: is within constitutional power\nof courts to frame rules governing admittance\nto practice.\nAs to the charge that in the face of the\n?stablishment of this rule by himself\nJudge Wilfiey did ta?t require his alleged\nfavorite,. Tailed States Attorney Bassett.\nto iak< t!;e examination, hut permitted\nhim to represent private litigants before\ni he court on the strength of his superior\ni itctit to practice in behalf of the government.\niiie committee iinds that the failure\nt\" apply the common test of examination\njo Mr. Bnsactt was obnoxious, irregular\narid unlawful, but that it%was a mistake\nof judgment and not actuated by\ncorrupt motive.\nRegarding the charge thai Judge Wilf>\\\nmaligned and slandered the Shanghai\nbar. the committee iinds that If he did so\nflint was a personal and not a judicial\na< t.\nDiscussing the charge that Judge Wilfiey\nused the threat of disbarment to\nI crsuade Mr. Andrews to dissolve his\nlaw partnership with Attorney Brooks, a\nn an low in the judge's regard, the report\nsays:\nAn attempt upon the part of a judge\nto cerce an officer of his court to his\nwill by a threat of disbarment would be\nan o{Tense of the gravest judicial character.\"\nIgnorance of Law.\nThe charge which appeared to the com\nn.iuee to ue ine most serious 01 an me\ntwc-my-nlne was that Judge Wilfley perii.\nit'-'i the prosecution ami conviction of\nan .American in Shanghai on tlie felony\nbarge ?'f assault with a deadly weapon,\nwhen the a. .-anIt in fact was committed\nv. Hi .in in load-il levinver and hence was\ntne't wiitt tl.e law defines as a simple\na-.-an and that alter eonvlction lie re;\nve.; 'i ada.it tin- defendant to bail pending\nai ;e hut kept him contineil in a\n.1 tor nim months. The committee\nfinds thai l!.i. Juuge Wflfiey piu\ndml from if*no: i. nf tin law and not\nf <?:n the mah'ii: i ve assigned bv Ids\nei.s?-rs ami t hat 1 engli ignoranee of\nthe law lines not ex.-use a malefactor beto.e\na lit. it does preserve the judge\nfrom impeai-hment in tlie absence of evil\nintent.\"\nTic report silts in commenting on the\nurges;\nIt is obviously true that an aggrrgat\non entirely i>-s;il arts may develop itil\"\na v's'ein <>f lyratmv and oppression:\nfhiit a.i inequitable exercise of juC:\nia' discre; ion may convert the ma<\niin ry of j slice into an ngine of deypotic\nand autocratic power. Tliis may lie\nam-oiiip l ml Without the taint of indlvid.ia!\ncorruption and with a laudable\n1'iipose of purifying a community and of\ninaugurating civic reform.\n\"Tenor to vil-d.?ers. it\" purchased a!\nt ptim- of judicial fairness and over?\nra.tied i? t;:i! authoiity. is aeliieved at too\njir- a! an expense, for il defeats its own\nhigh aim and warps the very fabric of\n1 law Its.lf.\n\"The temptation of an honest judge to\n\"heml once the law to his authority, to do\noft t i]it tt l? wt niii? is; fwi iiflil\nV r\"\nwith su h danger to oil! whole system j\n1 justice ti.at ii must merit the\ncondemnation of every mind.\nBasis of the Charges.\nSin n ;i< s of legal oppression ami of\n.use of judh'i.il discretion lie at the\nfoundation of tiu-se charges. They are\nmade before the House of Kepresentativs\nin the form prescribed by law and custom\n:i: d ,i!?- presentcd as a question of high\nprivilege upon the solemn responsibility\no\" a member of tlie House. Charges so\npresented against this court have a peculiar\nami dangerous significance. In this case\nthey are dismissed as falling short of inipeaerahle\noffenses by what we believe to\nli?- sound principles of legal construction,\nand .ludg Wiltleyir thereby denied every\nopportunity for ilmeiise. lie can tile no\naus\\\\\"! and make no denial nor explain to\nin?- House the legality ot necessity for his\n.action.\n\"These charges therefore stand uieontrov.utcil.\nand if Ids judicial acts in the\nfuture a i marked by the I igomtis ami intlcxiidi\ni,:oslnuss imputed to him. they\nwill hung as a portentous cloud over this\ntew i oil. i, impairing the usefulness of\nJ Willi'-'., initialing the admiulsiru\n11 wisu aim ciiuilmiging llif In\\<\ni il ?r.? i i- aii instil miotic.\"\nDeath cf Andrew A. Kennedy.\n..f Tb?* Slir.\nXI V ATTSVI U.K. M.I Mareh I'V l'.ioS.\n\\r.?l!.-.r A Kenn.tly. a nieehanio em-j\npin ..I in tin' ordnance bureau of the\nI if.! States invi yard at Washington,\n.li -.l Wine av.-nir* h\"re\ninst ntgi't. an ill'toys of alioitt two\nv.. K Ih 10:11 i... ti .l .1 >--v -i I'Oltl. which\ni j.i;t in uiiio;ii.i. 11? f'-.-owi? ?l from\nt i.i111 i.'it Mi.'< uin'?-.l to a\nit w. .'kirss brought on by it., (lis-a\n|i. .a, ,i was ,il otji thirty-eight years of\nii..1 l.'.n.s a wife ami thr\"o young\n,1.1: i:. had boon a resident of\nJUattsvilh about two years.\nPROBINU FOUL MURDER\nHEARING OF TRIO IN CRIME\nNEAR WHEELING. W. VA.\nSpecial orrcs petitionee of The Star.\nWHEELING. W. Va.. March Si. 1!K?S.\nDevelopments are coming thick and fast\nin the case of the mitruer of Charles Bennett.\njr.. of New Kensington. Da.. for\nwhich I.ila Zane Cook. Charles Cook, her\nhoy husband, and \"Joe\" White, an associate.\nstand accused. The hearing of tiie\ntrio on the charge of first degree killing\ntook place in tit? O.tio county jail this\nmorning.\nIt is expected that this trial will hring\nforth some light upon the mysterious\ndeath of Ella Zone, a contain of lite accused\ngirl, whose dead body was found in\nthe willows near the bank of the river on\nWheeling Island, not ten yards from the\nspot where Charles Bennett was robbed,\nj beaten to death and his body cast into the\nj Ohio t iver. There were mysterious circumstances\nconnected with this case.\ni which occurred about three years ago,\nthat were never unraveled by tae authoriI\nties.\nThe mother (if the girl was grief-crazed\nover her shiI death. and is now m the\nState Insane Asylum. The victim, too.\nwas a direct descendant of Eben?zer\nZane. founder of Wheeling, anil Elizabeth\nZane. the heroine of Eort Henry in revolutionary\ntimes. Ella Zane left her home\none beautiful summer night and never returned.\nA few days later her hotly was\nrecovered, divested of almost all of her\nclothing.\nWhether or not there was foul play done\nj ?ti e girl the victim of some jea'ous rival\nin a love affair?or whether- there was\nsome other motive for the crime, or\nwhether rite girl, in a fit of temporary insanity\nor despondent y or grief over something\nthat was hidden in her heart and\nwhich she carried to the grave, committed\nsuicide, may never he known.\nTo strengthen the insanity plea that will\nprobably be offered by counsel for the defense\nof I.ila Zane Cook, these facts may\nbe brought up, and may lead to some developments\nof a sensational nature. The\ngitl is well educated, although her vivacity\nand fondness for outdoor life caused her\nto leave school while quite young, and in\nyears sli? has rearl hut little. Her associations\nfor two or throe years thave tint\nbeen the best.*-and according to the police\nsite was just finishing up a night of\nj carousal in Beilaire. Ohio, when site was\narrested, following Cook's confession.\nCell Life Telling on Girl.\n'Die confinement of her cell Is telling on\ntlie girl. It was hoped by counsel for the\ndefense to secure an early hearing, in the\nhope of admission to hall, but with the\nstrong evidence already given there is\nlittle possibility of that. Reports that\nsite has been deserted by Iter wealthy\nand influential relatives tire unfounded.\nAlthough they are not permitted to call\nupon iter in the jail, daily tokens in the\nway of flowers, delicacies, etc.. ar? sent\nto Iter through the turnkey. Site still has\nho fie of securing iter freedom when arraigned\nat the preliminary hearing. Site\nsays it is a cruel plot of iter vindictive\nyoung husband to get iter into trouble because\nho knew that he could not elude\nthe law much longer, and tried *to save-his\nneck from lite gallows rope by Itis confession.\nOn the other hand, the boy sticks to his\nr.ftirin'i I ct /vei- rxl eor-Uau t Itr. i Kl,\\\nui ik,ni<ii uiiu i ii co ilir- Jiui I i ill\"\ndetails without a whimper. His demeanor\nhas not changed: he shows no sign of\nremorse over his deed or fear of his f^te.\nlie appears to believe that the worst will\ncome, but displays wonderful fortitude.\nHe is constantly singing popular strains\nhe recently sang on the vaudeville stage,\nor whistling softly to himself in the contines\nof his gloomy cell.\nHis widowed mother is in dire want,\nand owes her very existence to kindhearted\nneighbors. His aged grandmother,\nwho comes from sturdy German stock,\nonce well-to-do. hut now reduced to poverty.\nis lying near death in their rafhsiiackle\ncottage in the East End. An invalid\nfor several years, the new sorrow\nwill cause her d^ath. The boy was the\npride of her heart.\nCharges It All on Woman.\n\"Ah. chief. I was making good money\nin the south.\" he told Chief of Police William\nCJemans, \"and was sending every\ncent I could rake and scrape to my dear\nmotiier and old grandmother. But the\nold desir? for tiie piano music of Wheeling's\nsaloons and the piteous appeals of\nLi la made me homesick. It was Lila\nwho put me here. With her. she got my\nmoney. I forgot the folks over there at\nhome.\"\nThe boy ended this with a sigh, but Ids\neyes were tearless. He evidently believes\nthat but for her he could have made a\nman of himself, but with his life and\ncareer blighted he seems ready to face\nanything in order to bring his hopes' destroyer\nto justice.\nIn Wheeling's criminal history there has\nnever been a case in which so much interest\nwas attached, and the outcome of\nthe hearing will be awaited with expectancy\nby thousands.\nVETERAN ENGINEER DEAD.\nJ. C. Loudenslager Dies of Paralysis\nat His Home in Baltimore.\nBA I.TIM OK K. March 25?Mr. Jesse\nLoudensluger. one of the oldest engineers\non the Baltimore and Ohio railroad, is\ndead as the result of a stroke of paralysis.\nMr. I.oudenslager was first stricken liveweeks\nago while on his engine in th?\n[yards at Mount flare, and was tffken to\nIris home, at IMU Wilkens avenue, which\nhe never again lett. the second stroke,\nwhich occurred Monday, being fatal.\n\"I'ncle Jess.\" as he was known among\nthe Baltimore arid Ohio men. bad been\non the road for thirty-eight years, for the\ngreater part of which he was an engineer.\nHe was running passenger trains\nwhen the old type of engine was in\nI use and two hours between Baltimore\nj and Washington was considered great\nspeed. But old age brought him to the\nMount flare yards as a freight engineer\nabout live years ago. He bad a bronze\nntedal from th? Baltimore and Ohio, indicating\nhis service of tw\"nty-iive years\nwith the road.\nMr. l/oudenslagt r was horn in farroH\ncounty in I.Vil and went with the Baltimore\nand Ohio when eighteen years old.\nHe is survived by his father. William J.\nI.oudenslager. aged eighty years, tlie old?\nti-ocl til >1 i<-n Affli-lif {ft t 1 wl a nrl\niri iriil C'i ti 141 i ij*; nuu\nwho is himself ill. The oilier survivors\narr his widow (May Kstellet and two\nsons, one of them being Charles K.\nLoudenslager. the second baseman for\ntiie Rochester Eastern League base bail\nteam. The other son is J. Frank Loudenslager\nof Kelly Loudenslager. proprietors\nof Kelly's Hotel.\nSERMON LEADS TO ARREST.\nHusband Charges Preacher Libeled\nHim at Funeral.\nREADING. Pa.. March 25.?The Rev.\nMarvin H. Stettler. pa3tor of St. Paul's\nLutheran Church, one of the best known\nclergymen in the Pennsylvania Lutheran\nministcrium. wus arrested yesterday on\nthe charge of criminal libel. He gave $500\nbail for appearance.\nJcremiali Werner Is the prosecutor. His\nwife was burled several days ago. and the\nfuneral service was held in SI. John's\nChurch. More than tioo people were present.\non that occasion, instead of Unusual\nfuneral sermon, the Rev. Mr. Stettler.\nit is charged, delivered a tirade\nagainst tin* bervavcd husband in which\nii is charged he inaiie remarks uf wiiicii\nilie following are examples:\nl.oo.'' at him' There he sits and doh't\nem to and yet what did lie do?\nWhy. he knocked down ids wife a week\ntv-foie she was taken ill. Me did not\nfurnish her with clothing and shoes lit\nto go to church.\"\nThe husband denies the preacher's\ncharges -and announces that lie will sue\nj for damages.\nI Industrial Exposition by the Blind.\nInvitations are out for an at home and\nj industrial exhibition of the Columbia\n|?ol\\technic Institute for the Blind, to he\nin hi at the institute. I^ov s'reet. next\nI Thursday from to t? o'e'o< k. Tncro will\nhe demonstrations, ineludtng t Idilld\nsetting type, operating printing presses.\nJ sewing machines ami other machinery;\nI typewriting and Brialle writing.\niPLEAFROM KENTUCKl\n\nWant Federal Aid Against the\nNight Riders.\n\nPETITION TO PRESIDENT\nWould End the Carnival of Arson\n\nand Murder.\nI\n\nI GRAND JURY TAKES A HANI\nJudge Refuses to Offer a Reward foi\nthe Slayers of Harlan\n\nHedges of Carlisle.\nOWKXTOX. Ky.. \\laroli '2~>.?Owenton\nwas visile.! early today by \"night riders.\"\nwho set tire 10 three large tobacco warej\nhouses, causing a loss of about $.\"().tNN\ni and destroying lSO.tNHi pounds of tobacco\nin addition to three buildings,\ni Tiie first building set on fire was the\nI big new K?|iiity warehouse, owned by a\nI stock company. This had in it aboul\nhNi.ut.iti pounds of pooled tobacco and 5?V\ntNNi pounds of independent leaf.\nProm the Kqulty warehouse the flames\nspread to the American Tobacco Comi\npany and a smaller independent house.\nNeither of these had any tobacco it,\ni litem, however, and the principal loss h\non the Kqultv house. The loss is partly\ncovered by insurance.\nPetition to Roosevelt.\nKKXIXGTOX. Ivy.. March The failure\non the part of the state authorities u\nrun down perpetrators of outrages conij\nmitted by \"niglit riders\" culminated yesj\nterday in a dire. appeal to the President\ni of tile 1'nited States for federal inter.\nference in Kentucky, in the form of a pei\ntit ion prepared by leading men of i.exingj\nton and central Kentucky, which is being\nput into ftii'cuiatinn throiigiiout tliis sec!\ntion.\nThe petitioners are sVware tliat tiie Pres:\nident can take no action unless the governor\nso requests, hut they say it is tlieii\npurpose by tliis means to bring tile twc\ni executives together in t.ie matter. The\ni petition follows:\nI \"To the lion. Theodore Roosevelt. Presii\ndent of the Cnited States, Washington.\nL>. f*.:\n\"Your petitioners, all of whom are citizens\nand residents of Kentucky, respect 'fully\nrepresent to you the turbulent conditions\nof civil affairs in this state.\n\"The conditions in tliis community have\nbeen fully set out in the newspapers and\nthe fact that those farmers who desire\nI to grow tobacco are prevented from doing\nso on account of force and violence and\nthe destruction of plant beds and burning\nof barns lias grown into the burning ol\nI dwelling houses, to which crimes has been\nadded murder,\nj \"We desire to further represent to your\nexcellency the fact that the .state governj\nincut is totally incapable of \"handling the\nsituation which becomes graver every\nday. The grand jury refuses to find indictments\nand the courts are unable to\npunish those guilty of crimes already committed.\n\"I'nder all circumstances we believe tlie\nnational government should take such\nsteps as may he necessary to bring about\npeace and safety of life and property in\nthe state of Kentucky, thus guaranteeing\nto each citizen the right of life, liberty\nand the pursuit o 1 happiness under the\nlaw. and to this end we respectfully, but\nearnestly, solicit your assistance and coi\noperation.\"\nNight Riders Indicted.\nHOPKIX3VTI.LE. Ky.. March 2\"?--Th<\nChristian county grand jury yesterday\nafternoon returned indictments agains:\nHerman Ric hard Crenshaw, a prominent\nTrigg county farmer, and Mat Gholston\nsr.. of this county, a half-breed Indian\ncharging them with being members ol\nthe night rider hand that raided Hopkinsville\nlast December, destroying property\nI valued at $HOO,(SOO, wounding one man an i\nwhipping another and shooting up the\nI town.\nSeveral other indictments for night rider\ni offenses were also returned, but the names\nwere withheld until warrants of arrest arc\nserved.\nI Crenshaw is under bond and Gholston\ni is in jail.\nJudge Refuses to Offer Reward.\nCARLISLE. Ky.. March 23.?Judge Mc!\nXeal has refused to offer a reward for th?\narrest and conviction of any of the night\nriders who Friday night shot and killed\nHarlan Hedges, an independent tobacco\nfarmer, living near Carlisle.\nHe -declared he will not do so unless\nsanctioned by the fiscal court, now in\nsession.\nPRICE OF MEAT SOARS.\nPacking Trust King Gleefully Anticipates\nGood Times.\nCHICAGO, March 23.?J. Oglen Armour.\none of the packing trust kings,\nreturned yesterday from New N ork in\nmost optimistic spirits as to the return\nof prosperity. The priee of all kinds of\nmeat began to soar. Dressed beef went\nup $i a hundred. Mutton and lamb took\non an added value of from 3 cents to\n3 cents a pound. I'ork. cheapest of all\nmeats, had 2 cents a pound ta?-ked on.\nThe failure to boost pork higher is due\nto the fa.-t that Chicago has received\nthis winter more hogs than iu four\nyears.\nMr. Armour then made the public\nhappy by saying: \"I found sentiment\ngreatly improved in New York over\nwhat it was one month ago. No v there\nj is a complete ehangb. The opening of\nthe Knickerbocker Trust Company\ni se-'tus to have li.-irl iwat infl-.i ?iw?? r?ti\nsentiment, ;imi sentiment is a wonder'\nful factor in business.\n\"I believe that we have touched the\nbottom and have turned the earner.\nRailroad earnings are as poor as they\n<-an be. and the next change will be for\nthe better. I believe that from this\ntime busine^ will show impr jvement.\nI don't mean there will be any sudden\nchange, or that it will be in two weeks,\nthree weeks or three months, for that\nmatter, but if we have good r rops\neverything will be better, and there is\nno telling what will happen next year.\"\nKANSAS CITY. March -_'o.?The prices\n'of all meats except pork were advanced\nin many retail markets here yesterday.\nAn advance in pork may be expected\nwithin a day or two. Beef is up to a\ncents a pound for all ehoice cuts, lamb\nhas been advanced about the same. The\ncheaper kinds of beef, like chuck steak\nor .boiling pieces, are advanced 1 to\ncents a pound. The cause of the\nadvance is given as the scarcity of fat\ncattle in the southwest.\n\"There are as many cattle in the\ni southwest as customary,\" sahl George\nt K. Cole, a live stock commission mer;\nchant, \"hut they are not fat cattle. It\nwill he several months before tno sdiort|\nage is relieved. Meunwhilc the price\" ol\ni beef probably will reach a point where\nriumv families will have to quit eating\nj it.\"\nu;\nII\nI\nDO XT\nli i WALK\nThere's 1\nNothing i look\nBetter lSE_\nFor Coughs and ^IKLS\nC'olds than lOOTII;\nHaie's Honey l l l';s\nof llorohouml wtvvi\nanil Tar\nC --J\nWoodward\nNew York?AVAST\n1! Easter Cards, Booki\nMain Floor,\nj\nI\nPre=Easter\nFreoclhi I\nAnd Infant\nm SPECIAL display tS\nembroidered Frern\nCiothe